Feature: the bc-emit work-done wrapper's scenario-hash staleness check (Check 3) is evaluated against the FETCHED origin/main tree, not the stale local checkout — a BC whose local main lags origin/main does NOT false-refuse on an already-reconciled scenario, and any unavoidable refusal names "sync local main" as the cause

  Corrects the source-freshness of the scenario_hashes-match staleness
  precondition (Check 3) of the CLI-layer "bc-emit work-done" wrapper
  (ADR-036 D1/D2). Check 3 today recomputes "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tags
  against the BC's LOCAL working tree. When the BC's primary checkout local
  main lags "origin/main", that local tree is STALE: a scenario block that
  was reconciled on "origin/main" (its on-disk tag corrected to reproduce
  against its as-committed body) still appears in the lagging local checkout
  with the OLD body and/or OLD tag, so the local recompute mismatches and the
  wrapper refuses — naming the scenario-hash recompute-mismatch and
  misdirecting the operator toward "--force" or hand-editing an already-correct
  scenario, when the real remedy is to fast-forward local main to "origin/main".

  This is the SOURCE-FRESHNESS arm, and is DISTINCT from the SCAN-SCOPE arm
  scenario 225 (@aabbc009bad6fe86, lead-s8j2) closes: 225 narrows WHICH
  scenarios Check 3 evaluates (the dispatch's own assigned set, not a global
  features/ scan); this fixes WHICH TREE Check 3 reads (the fetched
  "origin/main" tree, not the stale local checkout). Work-scoping alone does
  NOT subsume this: a dispatch's OWN assigned scenario whose tag was
  reconciled on "origin/main" still false-refuses when the local checkout
  lags, because the recompute still reads the stale local body/tag.

  This mirrors the Check 2 reachability posture scenario 177 (@461d6066ef7dca0a)
  already pins — that check performs "git fetch origin" and evaluates against
  "origin/main" precisely so a stale local view does not yield a false result.
  Check 3 must carry the same freshness guarantee. The recompute itself remains
  scenario-block-only canonicalization via the in-process
  "scenarios.hash.compute_scenario_hash" delegate (ADR-036 D3 / scenario 179),
  never the Feature-line-included wire form, and the refusal-text posture stays
  BC-self-resolve (scenario 180): the "sync local main" remedy is the BC
  fast-forwarding its OWN checkout, never the lead acting on BC-repo state.

  Origin: lead-b2iz mechanism_observation. Dogfooding bc-emit to sign off
  lead-b2iz, the first emit was REFUSED naming
  bc_implementer_sections.feature @1758fe166d638cda recompute-mismatch — a
  scenario NOT in b2iz's set and already reconciled to @3314ed2e84ad54c5 on
  "origin/main". Real cause: the BC's local main was 6 commits behind
  "origin/main", so Check 3 read a stale features/ tree. Fast-forwarding local
  main to "origin/main" resolved it with no "--force". This runs inside the BC
  container against the BC's own tree (ADR-036 D2, ADR-018). "shop-msg respond"
  stays a pure messaging primitive; the bare "--force" path (scenario 181)
  remains the escape valve.

  @scenario_hash:613ddd886f6dc431
  Scenario: bc-emit work-done's scenario-hash staleness check is evaluated against the fetched origin/main tree — a lagging local checkout does NOT false-refuse on a scenario that is consistent on origin/main, any unavoidable refusal names local-main-behind-origin/main and "sync local main" as the cause, and a scenario genuinely stale on origin/main still refuses
    Given a dispatched work_id whose own assigned scenario set is committed and reconciled on the BC's "origin/main" — each block's on-disk "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag reproduces against its as-committed body on "origin/main" via scenario-block-only canonicalization
    And the BC's primary checkout local main is behind "origin/main" — its HEAD is an ancestor of "origin/main" HEAD — so the local working tree carries a STALE version of one or more of those scenario blocks whose on-disk "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag does not reproduce against the stale local body
    When the BC invokes the "bc-emit work-done" wrapper for that work_id
    Then the wrapper performs a "git fetch origin" and evaluates the scenario-hash staleness check (Check 3) against the fetched "origin/main" tree — mirroring the Check 2 reachability posture (scenario 177) — and does NOT refuse on a scenario block that is consistent on "origin/main" but stale only in the lagging local checkout
    And if the wrapper instead refuses, its named-cause error identifies local-main-behind-origin/main as the primary cause and directs the BC to fast-forward (sync) its OWN local main to "origin/main" and re-emit — it does NOT name the scenario-hash recompute-mismatch as the cause, and does NOT direct the BC toward "--force" or toward editing the already-reconciled scenario
    And a scenario block in the dispatch's own assigned set that is genuinely stale on "origin/main" — its on-disk "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag does not reproduce against its as-committed body on "origin/main" HEAD — still exits non-zero, does not invoke "shop-msg respond work_done", and names the scenario-hash staleness check as the cause, not masked by the local-staleness handling
